7 ABSTRACT Predicting mortality has been used in hospital management and can be defined as a very complex task. It is still the task of evaluating the likelihood that someone will die while they are in a medical facility, especially in intensive care units. Predicting mortality relieves the professionals of the doubts about the number of resources available, care, and of the exact details that are correlated with the medical standards of care. The incorporation of all the pertinent clinical data into patient care still represents some obstacles and a couple of examples are the collection of data during their current visit, co-morbidity, and patient demographics. Furthermore, patient status is not stable; it is rather dynamic, which hampers the selection of suitable models that will perform well in dynamic settings with the evolvingpatientdata. The assessment of hospital mortality among Intensive-Care Units (ICUs) patients with heart failure (HF) enables a better and more efficient healthcare environment by implementing specific measures. This research will develop and validate a machine learning model by using linear and kernel classifiers to predict hospital mortality statistics. Medical and patient population data constitutes the dataset employed in this operation. The accuracy achieved by Logistic Regression (LR) proved to be the maximum among all the studied classifiers. The Logistic Regression produced performance metrics of 0.86 accuracy alongside 0.8610 AUC value which surpassed Linear SVC, Perceptron along with Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD). The PolyKernelSVC achieved an AUC score of 0.7986 while providing an accuracy rate of 0.80 and excelled as the most effective among the kernelclassifiers. Therefore, the research emphasizes the ability of machine learning to improve the quality of clinical judgments and to assist and protect patients in the intensivecare unit. 1 INTRODUCTION Reliable models that estimate hospital death rates are vital for any healthcare system as they help to predict patients' future conditions in the course of their stay. Timely intervention planning would not only enable better patient care but also facilitate the implementation of suitable measures at the right time. This chapter provides evidence for the needs of hospital death prediction together with issues raised by traditional methods. 1.1 The Value of Predicting In-Hospital Mortality In the medical field, inpatient mortality are a significant contributing element to a variety of causes. By identifying it, healthcare practitioners can better manage their resources and make sure that patients who are more likely to die receive the right care, potentially improving their result and averting issues (Rinta-Koski et al, 2018). Furthermore, mortality prediction models are essential for improving patient-family communication by giving hints about the anticipated prognosis. Additionally, the application of in-hospital mortality prediction results in quality improvement programs for healthcare institutions, wherein clinical practices' operational areas
8 are highlighted for improvement. Hospitals have planned treatments that are based on data to reduce mortality rates and improve patient safety and satisfaction by giving them data-based knowledge (Wang et al, 2022). Mortality prediction models integrated in healthcare services facilitate patient communication, better utilization of resources, and also open up avenues for healthcare systems to be able to keep improving (Nisa and Chishti, 2023). 1.2 Conventional Methods for Predicting Mortality Risk assessment tools are instruments that clinicians and other healthcare professionals in the medical field employment to make a diagnosis of the likelihood of death in patients with certain diseases (Faisal et al, 2020). On the other hand, medical professionals still can be seen using statistical models and mortality tables that are based on the estimation of death rates. These tables are usually aimed at supporting activities in the area of pension schemes for the workforce, life insurance companies, and other similar organizations (Nisa and Chishti, 2023). Among the most important things that are taken into account are age, gender, and thewayinwhich. The figure shown here provides data on how people of different ages and genders in Australia spend their leisure time. It also shows how people of various ages and genders allocate their leisure time among different activities. The chart clearly depicts the ages and genders of those who like social or physical activities and the ages and genders of those who prefer to spend time alone. The data is to carry out public health policies and strategies which may be to understand mortality trends among various demographic groups and geographic regions (Chen et al., 2023). Now, the article from which we are discussing may count advanced epidemiological approaches among those very helpful in determining mortality risks, though their precision yield is far less than that of contemporary machine learning methods. Machine learning methods are able to produce more accurate results than traditional methods such as epidemiology. To make reliable forecasts, machine learning models commonly use multiple data sets and variables (Mekkodathiletal.,2023). 1.3 Obstacles in Predicting In-Hospital Mortality The multiplicity of sources of data, which have electronic health records, are medical imaging, and laboratory test results, is a prominent issue. These sources of data are usually in various formats. It may be an extremely tedious job to unify and standardize these data for analytics (Bozkurt and Asuroglu, 2023). Furthermore, models have to be constantly refreshed as patients' health situations keep fluctuating dynamically and they have to be designed so as to be able to adapt to the changes happening in the environment. Besides technical problems, moral issues also represent a serious barrier to the development of this kind of technology. The latter issues relate to patient consent and data confidentiality (Kangetal.2020). 1.4 Problem Statement

11 2 BACKGROUND RESEARCH Health care professionals are still worried about the early identification of symptoms that indicate that a patient may die in the hospital. This part of the literature review extensively discusses various methodologies not only for the forecasting of deaths but also for improving patient outcomes and efficient use of organizationalresources. 2.1 The function of kernel and linear classifiers in Predicting in-hospital mortality Due to their enormous input in the analysis of patient data, several classifiers are used in the classification of hospital mortality (Jaskari et al, 2020). The linear classifier employs a straight line to assign the patients to different classes based on their characteristics (El-Manzalawy et al, 2021). LDA aims to figure out the parameters that will maximize the difference between classes, at the same time minimizing the overlapping areas (Aldraimlietal,2020). Death prognosis predictor's very simple design is composed of linear classifiers, which have proved to be successful despite their simplicity (Sabahi et al, 2023). Therefore, the kernel classifiers also might be good instruments for the representation of complicated medical data (Kang et al, 2020). A classifier of this type can even identify variables of smaller dimension (Kono et al., 2022). To uncover the various hidden and non-linear connections among variables, the technique first breaks the original data down into small parts and then transforms them into a higher-dimensional space, which can be visualized (Xieetal,2017). Kernel classifiers greatly extend the prediction of in-hospital death over a wide range of patient data, such as vital signs, demographic characteristics, laboratory results, and medical records (Awad et al, 2017). By providing medical professionals with the necessary insights for data- driven decisions in patient management, it then enables them to carry out prompt treatments aired at reducing or avoiding adverseoutcomes. 2.2 Previous Studies on In-Hospital Morality Predication The paper written by Kong, Lin, and Hu (2020) presents a new development in the application of machine learning techniques to predict in-hospital mortality of patients in an intensive care unit with sepsis. The model was built based on 86 factors, including age, blood test results, and comorbidities. LR, LASSO, gradient boosting machine, and random forest methods were implemented to create the models. The AUCROCs for the individual models LR, SAPS II, Random Forest, LASSO, and gradient boosting machine were 0.829, 0.829, 0.845, 0.833, and 0.77, respectively. The gradient boosting machine model also showcased excellent diagnostic performance in the hospital death prediction task, and the machine learning models were highly accurate in theirpredictions. 16 2.3 Findings from the Literature Review The literature review outlined covers various machine learning methods for predicting mortality in different medical contexts that include sepsis. The paper talks about the death of patients in intensive care units (ICUs) with conditions like trauma, acute kidney damage (AKD), hemodialysis (HD), and transcatheter aortic valve replacement (TAVR). Several studies that were conducted for the purpose of predicting hospital mortality are briefly summarized in thetablebelow. Features that are extracted from clinical data and echocardiography can be utilized via several methods. The commonly used statistics in the evaluation are Fl score, the correctness of the test, the exactness of the test, and ROC (receiver operating characteristic). In some clinical cases, machine learning models' prediction abilities match the performance of human experts, and their functions are regarded as being better for diagnosing single risk. At the end of the investigation, the authors also mention possible solutions to missing values, feature selection, unbalanced data, and model optimization-which are all strongly related to the issuestheyaddress. 2.4 Connection to the Goal To date, predicting mortality amongst patients who have HE and are admitted to the intensive care unit (ICU) still represents an open issue in the literature, in spite of the fact that various investigations have utilized machine learning (ML) for the purpose of predicting the probability of death in different medocal contexts. It is necessary to perform direct comparison and evaluation of linear and kernel classifiers. The extent to which linear classifiers and kernel classifiers affect the performance among ICU-admitted heart failure patients has not been thoroughly discussed, although researchers may have looked at the effectiveness of one or two classes in a similar medical setting. Another issue is that previous studies, in general, do not provideafall assessment of the effect of different hyperparameter settings on the accuracy of models that foreseemorality.\ 2.5 Research Deficit The published research does not include a comprehensive comparison of linear and kernel classifiers for the task of predicting the in-hospital mortality rates of heart failure patients in intensive care units and also an investigation of the various effects of some linear classifiers on the modelperformance.

The intention is to provide medical professionals with the necessary instruments for making decisions in a way that they can allocate resources efficiently and intervene promptly in order to save these patients. Besides kernel classifiers like SVC, this work also employs a set of linear classifiers, for instance, LR, Linear SVC, Perceptron, and SGD Classifier. SVC Nu. Sigmoid Kemel SVC, RBF Kemel SVC, Poly Kernel SVC, and Linear Kernel SVC are all part of the ensemble that is used to predict an aggregated in- hospitalmortality. Finding the best hyperparameter settings for each classifier is also the main objective to improve the predictive performance of early monality prediction. Besides that, the goal is to evaluate the performance of linear as well as kernel-based classifiers in the early mortality prediction of ICU-treated HE patients and to compare their performances by using some measures like accuracy, precision, recall, Fl score,andAUCscare. Figure 5 Proposed Research Methodology 3.2 Description of the dataset To be able to predict hospital mortality accurately, a good dataset is definitely needed. The intention behind the dataset below is to build decision models that can correctly identify the outcome classes of patients according to the given characteristics. 18 of conditions for the prediction of in-hospital death. The dataset used in the experiment consists of 1177 rows and 51 columns containing information useful for in-hospital mortalityprediction. https://github.com/Tobai24/In-Hospital-Mortality-Prediction This dataset is aimed to estimate the risk of death during hospitalization and contains variables like age, gender, BMI, and comorbidities such as diabetes, atrial fibrillation, and hypertension. For extended study, it is also needed to measure biochemical elements like blood salt, calcium, chloride, and lactic acid, together with cardiac parameters like ejection fraction (EP). The "outcome" variable, which represents in-hospital death, consists of 1176 cases, out of which 1017 are survivors and 159aredeceased. 3.3 Selection of techniques A methodical approach will be implemented in collecting data through several machine learning classifiers that are then used to find out the best one. The classifiers used in this present work are a mixture of kernel classifiers and linear classifiers. The linear classifiers that are good algorithms for high-dimensional data handling are LR, Linear SVC, Perceptron, and SGD Classifier. Because they operate with input vectors and transform these characteristics into a higher dimensional space to visualize the data better by generating nonlinear surfaces, kernel classifiers like SVC, Nu-SVC, Linear Kernel SVC, Poly Kernel SVC, RBF Kernel SVC, and Sigmoid Kernel SVC have moreflexibility. LR is a type of linear classifier that is ideally suited for binary classification as it allows one to determine the probability that a sample comes from one of the two classes (Shipe et al, 2019). A linear Support Vector Classifier (SVC), also known as a linear SVC, labels data by maximizing the margin between classes and locating the best hyperplane (Nipaetal,2024). SGD Classifier is a Stochastic Gradient Descent based linear classifier which is very suitable for big data sets, but Perceptron is merely a linear binary classifier that makes weight changes based on the classification error with the training data (Begum and Narayan, 2023). SVC exploits various kernel functions to uncover non-linear relations in the data plane. While Nu- SVC uses alternative means to manage the number of support vectors, it is basically the same as SVC (Ksiqzek et al, 20). Similar to the linear SVC, a linear kernel SVC is naturally multi- class classificationcapable. RBF Kernel SVC employs a radial basis function kernel for learning non-linear patterns (Zhang et al., 2022); Poly Kernel SVC utilizes a polynomial kernel to find the relationships among variables (Nwegbu, 2023); and Sigmoid Kernel SVC applies a sigmoid kernel that is mainly used as an alternative to neural networks (Javeed et al., 2023). The performance of these classifiers will be enhanced in order to boost the accuracy of the hospital's ICU-admitted heart failure mortality rate. Furthermore, the study implements various techniques such as the Synthetic Minority Over-Sampling Technique (SMOTE) for solving the problem of class imbalancethatismostly one characteristic of datasets used in the medical field. The classifiers
19 are highly benefited from this approach as it allows them to learn from a more diverse dataset, which subsequently improves the classifiers' performance. The research is focused on using feature selection to improve the accuracy of linear and kernel classifiers so that the model's accuracy can be improved and better resource allocation and decision-making can be supported in the intensivecareunit. 3.4 The Oversampling Method SMOTE is a method which is developed for oversampling of the dataset to eject the problem of class imbalance. 3.4.1 The SMOTE Method SMOTE is the leading technique among many methods that are utilized for hospital mortality prediction based on supervised learning. SMOTE addresses the class imbalance problem in a model thus it leads to creating examples of the minority class so the model's prediction will be better. SMOTE enables the classifiers to learn a dataset that is more balanced by oversampling the minority class therefore the prediction of hospital mortality rates is improved (Ishaqetal., 2021). 22 Figure 9 SVC (Ali et al, 2018) One of the positives of SVC in this case is that it can handle not only linear but also non-linear relationships with the data. Besides, SVC can also see more complicated patterns in the data and the relations between them which linear models may not find. On top of that, SVC's feature of being useful in situations where healthcare datasets have unbalanced class distributions is a very important capability (Lietal.,2021). 3.6.2 Nu- SVC Nu-Support Vector Classification (Nu-SVC) is a type of SVC which was designed for solving classification problems and it is still capable of working with imbalanced datasets. Imbalancec datasets are the most frequent ones in hospital mortality prediction. Nu-SVC is different from the traditional SVM by a new parameter named nu, which is a lower bound of the support vect as well as an upper bound of the training error rate. This not only improves the model's outpul on hospital mortality but also allows Nu-SVC to efficiently solve problems where the number o examples of one class is bigger than the other one (Sharma andKumar,2022). Nu-SVC's capability of dealing with unbalanced datasets is one of its features which does not require class balancing or oversampling/undersampling and it is just the same in hospital mortality prediction. This is extremely significant in medical datasets where healing events are substantially more than death events (Lietal.,2022). 3.6.3 Linear Kernel SVC The Linear Kernel SVC algorithm in a high-dimensional space tries to locate the best hyperplane for classifying the data efficiently. For large datasets, the linear kernel is more efficient as it performs the dot product of t samples without actually changing them in any way, in contrast to other kernels like po or radial basis function kernels (Sadeghi, Banerjee, and Romine, 2018).
23 One of the primary advantages of Linear Kernel SVC when it comes to hospital mortalit prediction is feature interpretability. It is especially important in the medical field as the understanding of the decision behind the prediction is the main requirement (Ye. Zhang Jiang,2020). 3.6.4 Poly Kernel SVC Poly Kernel SVC, which employs a kernel function, is designed to solve non-linear data point problems in an effective manner. Due to its flexibility, it can detect various types of patterns and relationships that may be present in the numerous factors affecting hospital mortality rate, such as patient's personal features, medical history, and the treatments available (Zheng, Li, Lu, andRuan,2018). One significant benefit of Poly Kernel SVC is undoubtedly its compatibility with high dimensionality data. Such data is typically found in healthcare where numerous parameters are employed in a model to forecast mortality. The Poly Kernel SVC can create more accurate decision boundaries with the help of the higher dimensional feature space (Aka andSevli, 2022). 3.6.5 RBF Kernel SVC Since the majority of medical data sets are rather complex and could also have several nonlinear interactions, SVM with an RBF kernel is the best tool for the job of hospital mortality prediction as it is able to find complicated patterns in the given data set. RBF kernels are utilized to re-map the input data into another space where better decision surfaces are created in order to assist the classification of patients' mortality risk according to their clinical features (YA Ameretal.,2019). Moreover, RBF kernels are very affected by data changes and are able to easily adjust to them, thus this reduces the chances of overfitting and improves generalization performance. due to their flexibility, RBF kernel SVMs can be utilized to estimate hospital death rate as they are always able to give consistent results no matter what the patient's characteristics or health condition are (Abdaretal,2019). 3.6.6 Sigmoid Kernel SVC SVC with Sigmoid Kernel can also be utilized for medical data, where the relationships between the variables are complicated as it allows one to represent relationships that are not linear between the properties of the data. By its nature, the model is likely to be more compatible with the data, which could lead to an increase in the accuracy of mortality predictions (Jebadurai and Peter, 2017). In addition to this, since a patient's condition and results are determined by many factors, it is advantageous, if the resulting data are not linearly separated, which is quite frequent in the case of healthcare data (Sujathaetal.,2022).
24 3.7 Evaluation Metrics Accuracy: It indicates the number of correctly predicted results that were made out of all the decisions taken. Precision: It deals with the overall number of the positive cases, the model chooses, and the number of true positives ratio. Recall: The number of the actual positive cases, the models are, that are correctly recognized. F1 Score: The F-measure is the mean of these two (Xu, Zhang, and Miao, 2020) when both precision and recall are equal. AUC Score: It represents the extent to which the area under the ROC is able to signify the classes for the modelthatisformed. ROC Curve: True positive rate (Recall) along one axis and false positive rate along the other axis represent the classifier's performance (Valero-Carreras, Alcaraz, andLandete,2023). Confusion Matrix: It shows how well the classes of the built model can be predicted by the area underneaththe ROCcurve. Figure 10 Confusion Matrix model (Seol el at, 2023) Training Time: The period required for the preparation of the training dataset and training the model. Validation Time: This period was employed for adjusting the model's hyperparameters by running the model on the validation dataset. Testing Time: The duration necessary for predicting the test dataset's outcomes with the trained model in order to measure the accuracy of the model (Rahmad, Suryanto, andRamli, 2020) 3.8 Consideration of Ethical/Legal/Professional and Social This research on hospital mortality prediction via supervised learning algorithms is a topic that is ethically correct although the results will be negatively influenced by healthcare outcomes. New areas of investigation arealsomentioned. Previous studies goal is to predict in-hospital mortality have been concentred on many machine learning algorithms which are able to identify the best features, and they have obtained good results. In particular, Kong, Lin, and Hu (2020) indicated that models like RF and GBM are capable of reaching an AUC of 0.829. (2019) illustrated in their research that the utilized LR model was far more accurate than others and this statement was confirmed by an AUC value of 0.92 in the case of identifying death after transcatheter aortic valve replacement,orTAVR. These discoveries provide an overview of how various machine learning techniques could be employed to develop objectives with superior test accuracy across a broad spectrum of the healthcare sector. However, the current paper goes a step further and focuses on determining the hospital death rate of HF patients, who have been admitted to the ICU, with the help of linear as well as kernel classifiers. An evaluation of the outcomes indicates that the LR model had the highest accuracy. This finding is in agreement with the earlier studies where LR was recognized as one of the most efficient models. Yet, with the accuracy of 0.8, kernel classifiers, especially PolyKemelSVC, in this research, the analysis revealedsomepotential. The results of the performance studies of the classifiers have shown that the LR is the best linear classifier and the PolyKernelSVC is the best kernel classifier. An additional issue was found in previous research, highlighting the complex machine learning algorithms such as XBoost and DTs that, according to Li et al. (2021) and Sadeghi et al. (2018), yielded a high AUC score. Li et al., for example, revealed thatXGBoosthas better net benefit thresholds than the previous models, and DTs reached an accuracy of 0.93, as Sadeghi et al. reported. (2020) have also mentioned that RBFKernelSVC and SigmoidKernelSVC are models that havestruggledmost. I now have a clear understanding of how linear and kernel classifiers approximate in-hospital mortality while also understanding how the data used in the model differs. In order to get the greatest results out of each model, hyperparameter tuning was crucial. I also discovered that taking into account how these models are used in the workplace validated their viability in improving decision-making and patient health state prognosis. Another crucial topic to understand is the complexity of handling health care data, which calls for meticulous pretreatment. 6.2 Conclusion
